Executor service, and future.

An executor service is a managed pool of worker threads that you submit tasks to. This is the key mental shift from the last section: the pool owns the threads, and you just hand it work. It is the right abstraction for almost every concurrent workload you will ever write, and you should reach for it instead of raw threads by default.

You create one through the executors factory, which offers several common pool shapes. New-fixed-thread-pool gives you exactly n threads and queues any excess tasks. New-cached-thread-pool grows and shrinks, reusing idle threads. New-single-thread-executor runs everything sequentially on one worker. And, from Java twenty-one, new-virtual-thread-per-task-executor spawns a fresh virtual thread for every task, which we will unpack next. Because the pool's threads are non-daemon by default, you either wrap the pool in try-with-resources or call shutdown explicitly, so the virtual machine can actually exit.

When you submit a callable, you get back a future of V. A future is a placeholder for a result that might not be ready yet. Its main method, get, blocks the calling thread until the result is available, and you can pass a timeout to bound that wait. There is also cancel, to try to stop the task, and is-done, for a non-blocking check. A future is perfectly fine for a simple submit-and-wait pattern, but it does not compose. There is no clean way to say, when this finishes, do the next thing, without blocking a thread to wait. For that, you want completable future, which is exactly the next section.
